<!-- Learning Objectives -->
<div class="lesson-objectives">
<h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
<ul>
<li>Set up PHP development environment</li>
<li>Configure PHP for optimal development</li>
<li>Understand PHP installation options</li>
<li>Test PHP installation and configuration</li>
</ul>
</div>
<!-- Lesson Body -->
<div class="lesson-body">
<section class="intro">
            <h2>Introduction to Development Environments on Ubuntu</h2>
            <p>Welcome to our first session on PHP development environment setup, specifically tailored for Ubuntu Linux! Before we dive into writing PHP code, we need to establish a proper development environment on your Ubuntu system. Think of this as preparing your workshop—a chef needs a well-organized kitchen with quality tools readily available, and similarly, a PHP developer needs a properly configured environment where all components work together seamlessly.</p>
            
            <p>A proper Ubuntu PHP development environment allows you to:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>Write, test, and debug PHP code efficiently</li>
                <li>Simulate a production server locally</li>
                <li>Develop without an internet connection</li>
                <li>Experiment safely without affecting live websites</li>
                <li>Speed up the development cycle</li>
                <li>Take advantage of Linux's server capabilities</li>
            </ul>
            
            <p class="highlight">Ubuntu is an excellent choice for PHP development because many production servers run on Linux distributions. By developing on Ubuntu, you're working in an environment very similar to where your code will eventually be deployed.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="options">
            <h2>Understanding Development Environment Options on Ubuntu</h2>
            <p>There are several approaches to setting up a PHP development environment on Ubuntu, each with its own advantages and use cases:</p>

