            <div class="comparison">
                <table>
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Approach</th>
                            <th>Pros</th>
                            <th>Cons</th>
                            <th>Best For</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>XAMPP</td>
                            <td>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Quick and easy setup</li>
                                    <li>All components bundled</li>
                                    <li>Cross-platform consistency</li>
                                    <li>Graphical control panel</li>
                                </ul>
                            </td>
                            <td>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Less integration with Ubuntu</li>
                                    <li>Potential port conflicts</li>
                                    <li>Less customizable</li>
                                    <li>May differ from production</li>
                                </ul>
                            </td>
                            <td>Beginners, quick projects, or cross-platform development</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Individual Components</td>
                            <td>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Full control over each component</li>
                                    <li>Native Ubuntu integration</li>
                                    <li>System package management</li>
                                    <li>Can match production exactly</li>
                                </ul>
                            </td>
                            <td>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>More complex setup</li>
                                    <li>More maintenance</li>
                                    <li>Requires more Linux knowledge</li>
                                    <li>Switching PHP versions can be complex</li>
                                </ul>
                            </td>
                            <td>Experienced developers, production matching, learning server administration</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Docker</td>
                            <td>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Isolated environments</li>
                                    <li>Project-specific configurations</li>
                                    <li>Easy version switching</li>
                                    <li>Best production parity</li>
                                </ul>
                            </td>
                            <td>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Steeper learning curve</li>
                                    <li>Resource overhead</li>
                                    <li>Requires Docker knowledge</li>
                                    <li>More complex configuration</li>
                                </ul>
                            </td>
                            <td>Modern development workflows, team projects, complex environments, professional development</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
            
            <p class="analogy"><strong>Analogy:</strong> Think of these three approaches as different ways to prepare a meal. XAMPP is like a microwave dinner—quick, convenient, and everything's included, but less customizable. Individual components installation is like cooking from scratch—more work but complete control over ingredients and preparation. Docker is like meal prep with containers—organized, reproducible, and easy to share with others.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="xampp-setup">
            <h2>Setting Up XAMPP on Ubuntu</h2>
            <p>XAMPP (Cross-Platform, Apache, MySQL, PHP, Perl) is one of the most popular all-in-one packages for setting up a PHP development environment. It's designed to be easy to install and use, making it ideal for beginners.</p>
            
            <h3>Step 1: Download XAMPP</h3>
            <p>First, we need to download the XAMPP installer for Linux:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>Visit the official XAMPP website at <a href="https://www.apachefriends.org/download.html" target="_blank">https://www.apachefriends.org/download.html</a></li>
                <li>Scroll down to the Linux section and select the version with your preferred PHP version (e.g., 8.2.x)</li>
                <li>Download the installer (.run file)</li>
            </ol>
            
            <h3>Step 2: Make the Installer Executable</h3>
            <p>Open your terminal and navigate to the directory where you downloaded the installer:</p>
            <pre><code>cd ~/Downloads
chmod +x xampp-linux-*-installer.run</code></pre>
            
            <p>This changes the file permissions to make it executable.</p>
            
            <h3>Step 3: Run the Installer</h3>
            <p>Now run the installer with administrator privileges:</p>
            <pre><code>sudo ./xampp-linux-*-installer.run</code></pre>
            
            <p>A graphical installer will appear. Follow these steps:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>Click "Next" to begin the installation</li>
                <li>On the component selection screen, keep the default selections (or customize as needed)</li>
                <li>Click "Next" to confirm the installation location (/opt/lampp by default)</li>
                <li>Click "Next" to start the installation process</li>
                <li>Wait for the installation to complete</li>
                <li>When finished, you can choose to launch the XAMPP control panel immediately</li>
            </ol>

<div class="mermaid-converted" style="margin: 1.5rem auto; padding: 1rem; text-align: center; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%;">
<div style="margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 12px; color: #6c757d; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 1px;">Diagram
</div>
