            <h3>Step 1: Install Docker on Ubuntu</h3>
            <pre><code># Update package index
sudo apt update

# Install prerequisites
sudo apt install apt-transport-https ca-certificates curl software-properties-common

# Add Docker's official GPG key
curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /usr/share/keyrings/docker-archive-keyring.gpg

# Add the Docker repository
echo "deb [arch=$(dpkg --print-architecture) signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/docker-archive-keyring.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu $(lsb_release -cs) stable" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list > /dev/null

# Update package index again
sudo apt update

# Install Docker Engine
sudo apt install docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io

# Install Docker Compose
sudo apt install docker-compose-plugin</code></pre>
            
            <h3>Step 2: Add Your User to the Docker Group</h3>
            <p>This allows you to run Docker commands without sudo:</p>
            <pre><code>sudo usermod -aG docker $USER</code></pre>
            
            <p>Log out and back in for the changes to take effect, or run:</p>
            <pre><code>newgrp docker</code></pre>
            
            <h3>Step 3: Verify Docker Installation</h3>
            <pre><code>docker --version
docker compose version
docker run hello-world</code></pre>
            
            <h3>Step 4: Create a Project Directory</h3>
            <pre><code>mkdir -p ~/php-projects/my-first-project
cd ~/php-projects/my-first-project</code></pre>
            
            <h3>Step 5: Create Docker Compose Configuration</h3>
            <p>Create a docker-compose.yml file:</p>
            <pre><code>nano docker-compose.yml</code></pre>
            
            <p>Add the following content:</p>
            <pre><code>version: '3.8'

services:
  # PHP with Apache service
  php:
    image: php:8.2-apache
    container_name: php_dev
    ports:
      - "80:80"
    volumes:
      - ./src:/var/www/html
    depends_on:
      - mysql
    restart: always
    environment:
      - MYSQL_HOST=mysql
      - MYSQL_USER=phpuser
      - MYSQL_PASSWORD=phppassword
      - MYSQL_DB=phpdb

  # MySQL service
  mysql:
    image: mysql:8.0
    container_name: mysql_dev
    ports:
      - "3306:3306"
    volumes:
      - mysql_data:/var/lib/mysql
    restart: always
    environment:
      - MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD=rootpassword
      - MYSQL_DATABASE=phpdb
      - MYSQL_USER=phpuser
      - MYSQL_PASSWORD=phppassword

  # phpMyAdmin service
  phpmyadmin:
    image: phpmyadmin/phpmyadmin
    container_name: phpmyadmin_dev
    ports:
      - "8080:80"
    depends_on:
      - mysql
    restart: always
    environment:
      - PMA_HOST=mysql
      - PMA_PORT=3306
      - MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD=rootpassword

volumes:
  mysql_data:
    driver: local</code></pre>
            
            <h3>Step 6: Create PHP Source Directory</h3>
            <pre><code>mkdir -p src</code></pre>
            
            <h3>Step 7: Create a Test PHP File</h3>
            <pre><code>nano src/index.php</code></pre>
            
            <p>Add some sample PHP code:</p>
            <pre><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;PHP Docker Test&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;PHP Docker Test&lt;/h1&gt;
    
    &lt;?php
    echo "&lt;p&gt;Hello from PHP running in Docker!&lt;/p&gt;";
    echo "&lt;p&gt;PHP Version: " . phpversion() . "&lt;/p&gt;";
    
    // Test MySQL connection
    try {
        $host = getenv('MYSQL_HOST');
        $user = getenv('MYSQL_USER');
        $pass = getenv('MYSQL_PASSWORD');
        $db = getenv('MYSQL_DB');
        
        $conn = new PDO("mysql:host=$host;dbname=$db", $user, $pass);
        $conn->setAttribute(PDO::ATTR_ERRMODE, PDO::ERRMODE_EXCEPTION);
        echo "&lt;p&gt;Connected successfully to MySQL&lt;/p&gt;";
    } catch(PDOException $e) {
        echo "&lt;p&gt;Connection failed: " . $e->getMessage() . "&lt;/p&gt;";
    }
    ?&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
            
            <h3>Step 8: Create a Dockerfile for Custom PHP Configuration</h3>
            <p>If you need to install additional PHP extensions or customize the PHP environment:</p>
            <pre><code>nano Dockerfile</code></pre>
            
            <p>Add the following content:</p>
            <pre><code>FROM php:8.2-apache

# Install dependencies
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y \
    libpng-dev \
    libjpeg-dev \
    libfreetype6-dev \
    zip \
    unzip

# Configure and install PHP extensions
RUN docker-php-ext-configure gd --with-freetype --with-jpeg \
    && docker-php-ext-install -j$(nproc) gd \
    && docker-php-ext-install pdo pdo_mysql mysqli

# Enable Apache mod_rewrite
RUN a2enmod rewrite

# Set working directory
WORKDIR /var/www/html

# Expose port 80
EXPOSE 80</code></pre>
            
            <p>Then update your docker-compose.yml to use this Dockerfile:</p>
            <pre><code>  php:
    build: .
    container_name: php_dev
    # rest of the configuration remains the same</code></pre>
            
            <h3>Step 9: Start the Docker Environment</h3>
            <pre><code>docker compose up -d</code></pre>
            
            <p>This starts all the services defined in docker-compose.yml in detached mode (in the background).</p>
            
            <h3>Step 10: Verify Everything is Working</h3>
            <ol>
                <li>Open <code>http://localhost</code> in your browser to see your PHP application</li>
                <li>Open <code>http://localhost:8080</code> to access phpMyAdmin (login with root/rootpassword or phpuser/phppassword)</li>
            </ol>
            
            <h3>Common Docker Commands</h3>
            <pre><code># Start services
docker compose up -d

# Stop services
docker compose down

# Stop services and remove volumes
docker compose down -v

# View running containers
docker ps

# View logs
docker compose logs

# View logs for a specific service
docker compose logs php

# Access bash in a container
docker exec -it php_dev bash

# Restart services
docker compose restart</code></pre>
            
            <h3>Docker for Different Projects</h3>
            <p>One of the biggest advantages of Docker is that you can have different environments for different projects. Each project can have its own docker-compose.yml with different PHP versions, extensions, and configurations.</p>
            
            <p class="analogy"><strong>Analogy:</strong> Using Docker is like having separate, self-contained kitchens for each type of cuisine you want to cook. No more worrying about ingredient conflicts—your Italian kitchen won't interfere with your Thai kitchen, and you can easily switch between them or have both running simultaneously.</p>
        </section>
        
        <section class="comparison">
            <h2>Development Environment Comparison for Ubuntu</h2>
            
            <div class="comparison-chart">
                <svg width="800" height="400" viewBox="0 0 800 400" style="max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; margin: 0 auto;">
                    <!-- Background -->
                    <rect x="0" y="0" width="800" height="400" fill="#f5f5f5" />
                    
                    <!-- Title -->
                    <text x="400" y="30" text-anchor="middle" font-size="20" font-weight="bold">Development Environment Comparison</text>
                    
