                    <!-- XAMPP -->
                    <circle cx="200" cy="300" r="40" fill="#f96" opacity="0.7" />
                    <text x="200" y="300" text-anchor="middle" font-size="14" font-weight="bold">XAMPP</text>
                    <text x="200" y="320" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12">Easy Setup</text>
                    
                    <!-- Individual Components -->
                    <circle cx="500" cy="200" r="40" fill="#69f" opacity="0.7" />
                    <text x="500" y="200" text-anchor="middle" font-size="14" font-weight="bold">LAMP</text>
                    <text x="500" y="220" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12">Native Ubuntu</text>
                    
                    <!-- Docker -->
                    <circle cx="600" cy="100" r="40" fill="#6c9" opacity="0.7" />
                    <text x="600" y="100" text-anchor="middle" font-size="14" font-weight="bold">Docker</text>
                    <text x="600" y="120" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12">Containers</text>
                    
                    <!-- Legend -->
                    <rect x="650" y="50" width="120" height="80" fill="white" stroke="#333" />
                    <circle cx="670" y="70" r="10" fill="#f96" opacity="0.7" />
                    <text x="685" y="75" font-size="12">XAMPP</text>
                    <circle cx="670" y="95" r="10" fill="#69f" opacity="0.7" />
                    <text x="685" y="100" font-size="12">LAMP Stack</text>
                    <circle cx="670" y="120" r="10" fill="#6c9" opacity="0.7" />
                    <text x="685" y="125" font-size="12">Docker</text>
                </svg>
            </div>
            
            <p>The comparison above visualizes the trade-offs between different development environment approaches. XAMPP offers simplicity but less production parity, individual components (LAMP) offer better native integration but require more configuration, and Docker provides the best production parity but with a steeper learning curve.</p>
            
            <div class="recommendation">
                <h3>Recommendations</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>For beginners:</strong> Start with XAMPP to get familiar with PHP development quickly.</li>
                    <li><strong>For learning server administration:</strong> Try the individual components (LAMP) approach to understand how each piece works.</li>
                    <li><strong>For professional development:</strong> Invest time in learning Docker, as it provides the best workflow for modern PHP development.</li>
                    <li><strong>For teams:</strong> Docker is the best choice for ensuring consistent environments across team members.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="troubleshooting">
            <h2>Common Issues and Troubleshooting</h2>
            
            <h3>XAMPP Issues on Ubuntu</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Port conflicts:</strong> Apache may not start because port 80 is already in use
                    <pre><code># Find what's using port 80
sudo lsof -i :80

# Change XAMPP's Apache port
sudo nano /opt/lampp/etc/httpd.conf

# Look for "Listen 80" and change it to another port, e.g., "Listen 8080"
# Then restart XAMPP</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Permission issues:</strong> Can't write to the htdocs directory
                    <pre><code># Change ownership of the htdocs directory
sudo chown -R $USER:$USER /opt/lampp/htdocs</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>MySQL not starting:</strong> Usually due to port conflicts or corrupt data
                    <pre><code># Check if another MySQL instance is running
sudo lsof -i :3306

# If MySQL data is corrupt, you might need to reset it (warning: this deletes all data)
sudo rm -rf /opt/lampp/var/mysql/
sudo /opt/lampp/lampp restart</code></pre>
                </li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>LAMP Stack Issues</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Apache not starting:</strong> Check for configuration errors
                    <pre><code># Test Apache configuration
sudo apache2ctl configtest

# Check Apache error log
sudo tail -f /var/log/apache2/error.log</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>PHP modules not working:</strong> Make sure they're installed and enabled
                    <pre><code># List installed PHP modules
php -m

# Install a missing module (example: GD library)
sudo apt install php-gd

# Restart Apache after installing new modules
sudo systemctl restart apache2</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>MySQL connection issues:</strong> Check credentials and permissions
                    <pre><code># Try connecting to MySQL from command line
mysql -u root -p

# Check MySQL error log
sudo tail -f /var/log/mysql/error.log</code></pre>
                </li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Docker Issues</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Container not starting:</strong> Check logs for errors
                    <pre><code># View logs for a specific container
docker logs php_dev</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Volume mounting issues:</strong> Check paths and permissions
                    <pre><code># Verify volume mounts
docker inspect php_dev | grep -A 10 Mounts</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Network issues:</strong> Check container networking
                    <pre><code># List networks
docker network ls

# Inspect network
docker network inspect bridge</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Permission denied errors:</strong> Might need to fix file ownership
                    <pre><code># Access container shell
docker exec -it php_dev bash

# Inside container, check owner of files
ls -la /var/www/html

# If needed, change ownership
chown -R www-data:www-data /var/www/html</code></pre>
                </li>
            </ul>

