        <section class="best-practices">
            <h2>Best Practices for PHP Development on Ubuntu</h2>
            
            <h3>Security</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Change default passwords:</strong> Always change default passwords for MySQL, phpMyAdmin, etc.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Use environment variables:</strong> Store sensitive information in environment variables, not in code
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Regular updates:</strong> Keep your development environment updated to patch security vulnerabilities
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Development-only access:</strong> Limit development environment access to localhost or your internal network
                </li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Performance</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Optimize PHP configuration:</strong> Adjust php.ini settings for development performance
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Enable opcache:</strong> Speed up PHP execution with opcache
                    <pre><code># Install opcache
sudo apt install php-opcache

# Enable and configure in php.ini
opcache.enable=1
opcache.memory_consumption=128
opcache.interned_strings_buffer=8
opcache.max_accelerated_files=4000</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Use the right PHP version:</strong> Match your development and production PHP versions
                </li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Workflow</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Version control:</strong> Use Git for all projects
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Project isolation:</strong> Keep different projects separate, especially if they require different PHP versions
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Use Composer:</strong> Manage PHP dependencies with Composer
                    <pre><code># Install Composer globally
sudo apt install composer

# Initialize a project
composer init

# Install dependencies
composer install</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Error reporting:</strong> Enable detailed error reporting during development
                    <pre><code># Edit php.ini
error_reporting = E_ALL
display_errors = On
display_startup_errors = On
log_errors = On</code></pre>
                </li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Development Tools</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>IDE/Editor:</strong> Use a good PHP IDE or code editor (PHPStorm, VSCode with PHP extensions, etc.)
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Debugging:</strong> Set up Xdebug for step-through debugging
                    <pre><code># Install Xdebug
sudo apt install php-xdebug

# Configure Xdebug in php.ini
zend_extension=xdebug.so
xdebug.mode=debug
xdebug.start_with_request=yes
xdebug.client_host=127.0.0.1
xdebug.client_port=9003</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Code quality:</strong> Use PHP_CodeSniffer, PHPStan, or other code quality tools
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>
        
        <section class="practical-exercise">
            <h2>Practical Exercise: Creating Your First PHP Project</h2>
            <p>Let's apply what we've learned by creating a simple PHP project in each environment.</p>
            
            <h3>Exercise Objectives</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Create a simple PHP application that connects to a database</li>
                <li>Display dynamic content from the database</li>
                <li>Implement a simple form to add data</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Project: Task Manager</h3>
            <p>We'll create a basic task manager that allows adding and viewing tasks.</p>
            
            <h4>Database Structure</h4>
            <pre><code>CREATE TABLE tasks (
    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    title VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    description TEXT,
    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
);</code></pre>
            
            <h4>Project Files</h4>
            <p>We'll need three main files:</p>
            <ol>
                <li><code>index.php</code> - List all tasks</li>
                <li><code>add_task.php</code> - Form to add a new task</li>
                <li><code>db_connect.php</code> - Database connection script</li>
            </ol>
            
            <h4>Implementation Steps</h4>
            <p>For each environment (XAMPP, LAMP, Docker), follow these steps:</p>
            
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <strong>Set up the project directory</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>XAMPP: Create a folder in <code>/opt/lampp/htdocs/task_manager</code></li>
                        <li>LAMP: Create a folder in <code>/var/www/html/task_manager</code></li>
                        <li>Docker: Create a folder in your project's <code>src</code> directory</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Create the database connection file (<code>db_connect.php</code>)</strong>
                    <pre><code>&lt;?php
// Database connection parameters
$host = 'localhost'; // For Docker, use the service name: 'mysql'
$dbname = 'task_manager';
$username = 'root'; // Use appropriate credentials
$password = ''; // Use appropriate password

// Create connection
try {
    $pdo = new PDO("mysql:host=$host;dbname=$dbname", $username, $password);
    // Set the PDO error mode to exception
    $pdo->setAttribute(PDO::ATTR_ERRMODE, PDO::ERRMODE_EXCEPTION);
} catch(PDOException $e) {
    die("ERROR: Could not connect. " . $e->getMessage());
}
?&gt;</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Create the task list page (<code>index.php</code>)</strong>
                    <pre><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang="en"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
    &lt;meta charset="UTF-8"&gt;
    &lt;meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Task Manager&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;style&gt;
        body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; margin: 0; padding: 20px; }
        h1 { color: #333; }
        .task { border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border-radius: 5px; }
        .task h3 { margin-top: 0; }
        .add-button { display: inline-block; background: #4CAF50; color: white; padding: 10px 15px; 
                     text-decoration: none; border-radius: 5px; margin-bottom: 20px; }
    &lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Task Manager&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;a href="add_task.php" class="add-button"&gt;Add New Task&lt;/a&gt;
    
    &lt;div class="tasks"&gt;
        &lt;?php
        // Include database connection
        require_once "db_connect.php";
        
        // Fetch tasks from database
        try {
            $sql = "SELECT * FROM tasks ORDER BY created_at DESC";
            $stmt = $pdo->query($sql);
            
            if($stmt->rowCount() > 0) {
                while($row = $stmt->fetch()) {
                    echo '&lt;div class="task"&gt;';
                    echo '&lt;h3&gt;' . htmlspecialchars($row['title']) . '&lt;/h3&gt;';
                    echo '&lt;p&gt;' . htmlspecialchars($row['description']) . '&lt;/p&gt;';
                    echo '&lt;small&gt;Created: ' . $row['created_at'] . '&lt;/small&gt;';
                    echo '&lt;/div&gt;';
                }
            } else {
                echo '&lt;p&gt;No tasks found.&lt;/p&gt;';
            }
        } catch(PDOException $e) {
            die("ERROR: Could not execute query. " . $e->getMessage());
        }
        ?&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Create the task form page (<code>add_task.php</code>)</strong>
                    <pre><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang="en"&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
    &lt;meta charset="UTF-8"&gt;
    &lt;meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Add Task&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;style&gt;
        body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; margin: 0; padding: 20px; }
        h1 { color: #333; }
        form { max-width: 500px; }
        label { display: block; margin-top: 10px; }
        input[type="text"], textarea { width: 100%; padding: 8px; margin-top: 5px; }
        textarea { height: 100px; }
        button { background: #4CAF50; color: white; padding: 10px 15px; 
                border: none; border-radius: 5px; margin-top: 10px; cursor: pointer; }
        .back-link { display: inline-block; margin-top: 20px; }
    &lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Add New Task&lt;/h1&gt;
    
    &lt;?php
    // Process form submission
    if($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST") {
        // Include database connection
        require_once "db_connect.php";
        
        // Get form data
        $title = trim($_POST["title"]);
        $description = trim($_POST["description"]);
        
        // Validate input
        if(empty($title)) {
            $error = "Please enter a task title.";
        } else {
            // Insert task into database
            try {
                $sql = "INSERT INTO tasks (title, description) VALUES (:title, :description)";
                $stmt = $pdo->prepare($sql);
                
                // Bind parameters
                $stmt->bindParam(":title", $title);
                $stmt->bindParam(":description", $description);
                
                // Execute the query
                if($stmt->execute()) {
                    // Redirect to task list
                    header("location: index.php");
                    exit();
                } else {
                    $error = "Something went wrong. Please try again later.";
                }
            } catch(PDOException $e) {
                $error = "ERROR: Could not execute query. " . $e->getMessage();
            }
        }
    }
    ?&gt;
    
    &lt;?php if(isset($error)): ?&gt;
        &lt;p style="color: red;"&gt;&lt;?php echo $error; ?&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;?php endif; ?&gt;
    
    &lt;form action="&lt;?php echo htmlspecialchars($_SERVER["PHP_SELF"]); ?&gt;" method="post"&gt;
        &lt;div&gt;
            &lt;label for="title"&gt;Task Title&lt;/label&gt;
            &lt;input type="text" name="title" id="title" required&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
        
        &lt;div&gt;
            &lt;label for="description"&gt;Description&lt;/label&gt;
            &lt;textarea name="description" id="description"&gt;&lt;/textarea&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
        
        &lt;button type="submit"&gt;Add Task&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;
    
    &lt;a href="index.php" class="back-link"&gt;Back to Task List&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Create the database and table</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>XAMPP: Open phpMyAdmin at <code>http://localhost/phpmyadmin</code></li>
                        <li>LAMP: Open phpMyAdmin at <code>http://localhost/phpmyadmin</code></li>
                        <li>Docker: Open phpMyAdmin at <code>http://localhost:8080</code></li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Create a new database named <code>task_manager</code> and run the SQL query to create the <code>tasks</code> table.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Access the application</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>XAMPP: Visit <code>http://localhost/task_manager</code></li>
                        <li>LAMP: Visit <code>http://localhost/task_manager</code></li>
                        <li>Docker: Visit <code>http://localhost</code></li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </section>

        <section class="conclusion">
            <h2>Conclusion</h2>
            <p>In this session, we've explored different approaches to setting up a PHP development environment on Ubuntu:</p>
            
            <ul>
                <li><strong>XAMPP:</strong> A quick and easy all-in-one solution that works across platforms</li>
                <li><strong>Individual Components (LAMP):</strong> A more native Ubuntu approach with greater control</li>
                <li><strong>Docker:</strong> A modern containerized approach for the best isolation and consistency</li>
            </ul>
            
            <p>Each approach has its strengths and is suitable for different scenarios. As you grow as a developer, you might find yourself moving from the simplicity of XAMPP to the power and flexibility of Docker, especially for team-based and production-like environments.</p>
            
            <p>Remember that the goal of any development environment is to enable you to write, test, and debug code efficiently. Choose the approach that best fits your current needs and skill level, but don't be afraid to explore other options as your requirements evolve.</p>
            
            <h3>Next Steps</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Experiment with different PHP versions</li>
                <li>Try setting up virtual hosts for multiple projects</li>
                <li>Explore debugging tools like Xdebug</li>
                <li>Learn about version control with Git</li>
                <li>Explore more advanced Docker configurations</li>
            </ul>
            
            <p>In our next session, we'll dive into PHP syntax, variables, and data types, building on the environment we've set up today.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="resources">
